**Sec. 20001**
This section appropriates $10.4 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to improve military personnel quality of life, including $2.9 billion for housing allowances and $2 billion for the Defense Health Program. Specific allocations include $1 billion for military unaccompanied housing, $100 million for tuition and child care fee assistance, and $50 million for special pays and bonuses across the Army, Navy, Air Force, Marine Corps, and Space Force. The bill also amends title 10, United States Code, to temporarily increase the maximum percentage of value for privatized military housing projects from 33 1/3 percent to 60 percent and extends the authority for acquiring privatized housing until September 30, 2029. Additionally, $100 million is designated for the Defense Community Infrastructure Program and $62 million for modernizing childcare center staffing.

**Sec. 20002**
This section appropriates $18.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to enhance shipbuilding capabilities and industrial base resiliency. Major funding includes $4.6 billion for a second Virginia-class submarine, $5.4 billion for two additional Guided Missile Destroyers, and $2.7 billion for T-AO oilers, alongside $1.8 billion for Landing Ship Medium procurement. The bill also allocates $750 million for supplier development, $500 million for advanced manufacturing techniques, and $2.1 billion for purpose-built medium unmanned surface vessels. Furthermore, $1.5 billion is designated for small unmanned surface vessel production and $1.3 billion for expanding unmanned underwater vehicle production.

**Sec. 20003**
This section appropriates $22.3 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to advance integrated air and missile defense technologies and homeland defense. Significant funding includes $7.2 billion for military space-based sensors, $5.6 billion for space-based and boost phase intercept capabilities, and $2.55 billion for missile defense capabilities. The bill also allocates $2.2 billion for accelerating hypersonic defense systems and $1.975 billion for improved ground-based missile defense radars. Additionally, $408 million is designated for restoring and modernizing Army space and strategic missile test range infrastructure in the Indo-Pacific Command area.

**Sec. 20004**
This section appropriates $17.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to expand munitions production and strengthen the defense supply chain. Funding covers $400 million for long-range anti-ship missiles, $1 billion for expanding the one-way attack unmanned aerial systems industrial base, and $1 billion for creating next-generation automated munitions factories. The bill also provides $3.3 billion for grants and purchase commitments under the Industrial Base Fund, $5 billion for critical minerals supply chain investments, and $500 million for the Department of Defense Credit Program to subsidize up to $100 billion in loans. Specific allocations include $2 billion for critical minerals stockpiles and $500 million for counter-unmanned aerial systems programs.

**Sec. 20005**
This section appropriates $12.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to scale low-cost weapons and innovative technologies into production. Key allocations include $1.4 billion for expanding the small unmanned aerial system industrial base, $2 billion for the Defense Innovation Unit to scale commercial technology, and $1.5 billion for low-cost cruise missiles. The bill also provides $1 billion for accelerating the procurement of innovative technologies, $600 million for Strategic Capabilities Office programs, and $500 million to prevent delays in attritable autonomous military capabilities. Additionally, $1 billion is designated for the Department of Defense Credit Program to support capital assistance for critical technologies.

**Sec. 20006**
This section appropriates $380 million to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to improve the efficiency and cybersecurity of the Department of Defense. The funding includes $150 million for business systems replacement to accelerate financial statement audits and $200 million for deploying automation and artificial intelligence to support these audits. Additionally, $10 million is allocated to improve the budgetary and programmatic infrastructure of the Office of the Secretary of Defense, and $20 million is designated for Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency cybersecurity programs.

**Sec. 20007**
This section appropriates $12.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to enhance air superiority capabilities. Major funding includes $3.15 billion to increase F-15EX aircraft production, $750 million to accelerate the FA/XX aircraft, and $400 million to accelerate production of the F-47 aircraft. The bill also allocates $678 million for the Collaborative Combat Aircraft program, $600 million for Air Force long-range strike aircraft, and $500 million for Navy long-range strike aircraft. Additional funds include $361 million to prevent F-22 retirements, $127 million to prevent F-15E retirements, and $474 million to increase EA-37B production.

**Sec. 20008**
This section appropriates $13.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense and $3.5 billion to the National Nuclear Security Administration for fiscal year 2025 to modernize nuclear forces. Defense funding includes $4.5 billion for B-21 bomber production expansion, $2.5 billion for Sentinel ICBM risk reduction, and $2 billion for the nuclear-armed sea-launched cruise missile. The National Nuclear Security Administration receives $1 billion to accelerate facility construction, $750 million each for primary and secondary capability modernization, and $400 million for the sea-launched cruise missile warhead. Additional allocations include $148 million for D5 missile motor production and $120 million for domestic uranium enrichment centrifuge deployment.

**Sec. 20009**
This section appropriates $10.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to improve capabilities of the United States Indo-Pacific Command. Significant funding includes $3.65 billion for military satellites and their protection, $1.1 billion for infrastructure development, and $450 million for airfield development within the command's area of operations. The bill also allocates $1 billion for offensive cyber operations, $850 million for replenishing military articles, and $365 million for Army exercises in the Western Pacific. Additional funds cover $143 million for anti-submarine sonar arrays, $125 million for military space communications, and $350 million for space command and control systems.

**Sec. 20010**
This section appropriates $16.5 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to improve the readiness of the Department of Defense. Major allocations include $2.5 billion for Air Force facilities sustainment, $2 billion for Navy depot and shipyard modernization, and $1.5 billion for Army depot modernization. The bill also provides $2.118 billion for Air Force aircraft spares and repairs, $1.64 billion for Special Operations Command equipment, and $1.5 billion for increased depot and shipyard maintenance activities. Additional funding includes $400 million for Marine Corps readiness, $500 million for National Guard unit readiness, and $320 million for Joint Special Operations Command.

**Sec. 20011**
This section appropriates $1 billion to the Secretary of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to support border operations and counter-drug missions. The funds are designated for deploying military personnel, operations and maintenance activities, counter-narcotics support, and the construction of national defense areas. Additionally, the appropriation covers the temporary detention of migrants on Department of Defense installations in accordance with chapter 15 of title 10, United States Code.

**Sec. 20012**
This section appropriates $10 million to the Inspector General of the Department of Defense for fiscal year 2025 to monitor activities funded by this title. The oversight focuses on programs with mutual technological dependencies, related data management considerations, and those vulnerable to supply chain disruptions. The funds are available until September 30, 2029, to ensure accountability for the massive appropriations outlined in the preceding sections.

**Sec. 20013**
This section authorizes the appropriation of funds for military construction, land acquisition, and military family housing functions for each military department. It mandates that the Secretary of each military department submit a detailed spending plan by project to the Senate and House Armed Services Committees within 30 days of enactment. This provision ensures transparency and accountability for the expenditure of funds allocated for physical infrastructure projects across the armed forces. [end of text]


